### initial review — The changeset converts the browse-table row actions (Download/Delete/Move/Copy) from inline buttons into a '⋮' dropdown triggered by hover-revealed button or right-click, plus new CSS and an empty Actions column header. I reviewed a11y, responsiveness/layout, interaction/feedback, and visual consistency. The interaction model has several genuine defects: the trigger button is invisible to keyboard users and completely unreachable on touch devices (opacity:0 + pointer-events:none with no :focus rule), the position:fixed menu overflows the viewport near edges with no clamping, ARIA menu semantics (role=menu/menuitem, aria-controls, arrow-key nav, focus management) are missing, the Actions column header is now an empty unlabeled <th>, and the menu does not dismiss on scroll/resize. Smaller issues: non-unique accessible names, undersized touch target, and no explicit :focus-visible styling.
- [critical] Row '⋮' trigger is invisible when keyboard-focused and unreachable on touch devices — src/app.css:313-331
    .row-menu-btn is set to opacity:0 and pointer-events:none by default and only revealed by `.browse-table tbody tr:hover .row-menu-btn` or `.row-menu-btn[aria-expanded='true']`. There is no :focus/:focus-visible rule. Consequences: (1) A keyboard user tabbing to the button gets NO visible focus indicator (the button, including any outline, is fully transparent) until they happen to activate it — violating WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible and 2.1.1 Keyboard. (2) On touch devices there is no :hover state at all, so the button stays opacity:0 AND pointer-events:none, meaning it cannot be tapped — the entire row-actions feature (Download/Delete/Move/Copy) is unreachable on phones/tablets, violating WCAG 2.5.1/2.5.8. The trigger must be perceivable and operable without a hover-capable pointer.
- [high] Dropdown menu positioned at raw click coords overflows the viewport near edges — src/app/dom-builders.ts:225-236
    openMenu(x, y) sets `menu.style.left = x + 'px'; menu.style.top = y + 'px'` with position:fixed and no clamping. When opened via right-click near the right or bottom edge of the viewport (or via the button when the row is at the bottom), the 140px-min-width menu overflows off-screen, gets clipped, and/or introduces a horizontal/vertical scrollbar — making action items (especially Delete/Copy on the right edge) partially or fully invisible and unclickable. Standard dropdown behavior flips/clamps the menu to stay within the viewport.
- [high] ARIA menu pattern incomplete: no role=menu/menuitem, no aria-controls, no focus management, no arrow-key nav — src/app/dom-builders.ts:131-245
    The trigger uses aria-haspopup='true' and toggles aria-expanded, but: (1) it has no aria-controls pointing to the menu id, so assistive tech cannot associate the button with its popup; (2) the .row-menu container has no role='menu' and the items have no role='menuitem' (they are a plain div containing an <a> and <button>s), so screen readers do not announce a menu or menu-item semantics; (3) focus is not moved into the menu when it opens (neither the button click nor the contextmenu handler calls .focus()), so keyboard/screen-reader users are left on the trigger; (4) there is no Arrow Up/Down/Enter/Escape keyboard navigation between items (only default Tab order, which is non-standard for a menu). This degrades the experience for assistive-tech users below the expected ARIA Authoring Practices Guide menu-button/menu pattern.
- [high] Actions column header is now an empty unlabeled <th> — src/app/render-browse.ts:31
    renderBrowse changed `buildTable(['Name','Size','Modified','Actions'])` to `buildTable(['Name','Size','Modified',''])`. buildTable sets `th.textContent = label`, so the fourth header cell is now a completely empty <th> with no accessible name. Screen readers announce an unlabeled column header (or skip it), so users navigating the table by header cannot identify that the column contains row actions. The header should still convey 'Actions' to assistive tech even if it is visually blank (to match the now-icon-only cells).
- [medium] Open menu is not dismissed on scroll or viewport resize — src/app/dom-builders.ts:209-218
    The dropdown is position:fixed at viewport coords and its open state registers only document 'click' and 'keydown' (Escape) listeners. If the user scrolls the .results container (overflow:auto) or the page, or resizes the window while the menu is open, the menu stays pinned at its original viewport position, now detached from the row that owns it — confusing and potentially pointing at the wrong row's data. Standard dropdowns close (or re-anchor) on scroll/resize.
- [medium] Every row's trigger has the identical aria-label 'Actions' with no file context — src/app/dom-builders.ts:140
    btn.setAttribute('aria-label', 'Actions') is the same for every row. A screen-reader user navigating the table by name or hearing the button announced hears 'Actions, button' for every row and cannot tell which file/folder's actions it controls. Accessible names for repeated controls should include the item they act on.
- [medium] '⋮' trigger touch target (~20x28px) is below recommended minimum sizes — src/app.css:313-323
    .row-menu-btn has padding: 2px 6px, font-size: 16px, line-height: 1, yielding a tap area of roughly 20px tall by ~28px wide. This is below the WCAG 2.5.8 (AA) 24x24 CSS px minimum target size and well below the 2.5.5 (AAA) / platform 44x44 recommendation, making the already hover-gated trigger hard to hit accurately on touch even once it is made visible. The tappable area should be enlarged.
- [low] No explicit :focus-visible styling on the trigger or menu items — src/app.css:361-372
    Only :hover styles are defined for .row-menu-btn and .row-menu .btn (color/brightness/background on hover). There is no :focus-visible rule, so keyboard focus on the trigger or on the Delete/Move/Copy items relies on whatever the browser default outline is — inconsistent with the rest of the app, which uses explicit focus styling (e.g. .toolbar input:focus border-color:#6aa6ff, .toolbar label.btn:focus-within outline:2px solid #6aa6ff). For a consistent and reliable keyboard experience the menu should show the same focus affordance.

